Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Report on the audit
Preface
Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.
A focus of the work of the Court of Auditors should therefore be on the audit of this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone generates an estimated EUR 100 billion in tax losses per year in the European Union.
Already at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.
This allows the auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimise audit practice.
The value added tax (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, for the first time, the auditors of both states audited in parallel in the area of the USt.
The relevant audit report was published in 2008.
As VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, there is a need for close cooperation between the Court of Auditors, so that it can be fully assessed whether the measures taken are appropriate to effectively tackle VAT fraud.
The two auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit.
1. Introduction
Exam number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Object of examination: (CZ) Administration of USt (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), audit
Objective of the audit:
(CZ) The administration of VAT and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as Germany) should be examined, and the procedures applied by the financial authorities in the case of intergovernmental assistance should be examined.
(D) The purpose of the audit was to evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the Court of Auditors.
In addition, other exam fields linked to the USt should be processed.
The findings made should be compared in order to determine whether tax procedures can be optimised.
The audit period covered the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the audit period up to the conclusion of the audit.
2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany has agreed to carry out an audit of the administration of the USt.
During the previous parallel investigation, they had uncovered suspected cases involving intra-Community transactions,
which made another exam expedient.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two auditors made recommendations on the management of the USt.
The purpose of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to investigate the suspected cases identified.
The audit also dealt with other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of VAT receivables and the audit of large companies.
The Court of Auditors found that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous examination
• Recommendation 1: Taxable registration rules should be harmonised within the EU
In the first audit, the Court of Auditors compared the registration procedures for the USt in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxable persons within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of the existing databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of persons subject to VAT.
The draft also provided for common rules on the registration of taxable persons and their possible deletion.
The Court of Auditors expected Member States, in line with their decision in principle, to agree on appropriate rules to remove unreliable traders from the VAT system as early as possible.
Member States reached political agreement on the final version of the draft in ECOFIN.
The abovementioned common rules are no longer included in it, and the two Court of Auditors regret that.
They still consider such rules to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary notifications As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to Member States that the summary notifications (CMs) should in future be submitted on a monthly basis.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed in more time.
Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common system of value added tax for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has shortened the deadline for the levy of the ZM to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the transposition did not enter into force until 1 July 2010, so it did not transpose into national law the obligation to levy the ZM on a monthly basis in due time.
• Recommendation 3: Data comparison of the USt-Pre-Registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merging of the procedures for USt-Pre-Registrations and ZM The German Finance Administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Court of Auditors and set up a working group to work out possible solutions.
Work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Court of Auditors will monitor the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level In the course of the first audit, the two auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Court of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management."
2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
During the first audit, the Court of Auditors had jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or which had been explained differently by the taxable persons of the two States in the preliminary declarations (or VAT declarations) or ZM.
The Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the audit.
The audits by the tax offices (FÄ) of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.
The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, and appropriate measures have been taken by the respective financial administrations (including subsequent VAT fixes or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions
The audit also included highly risky intra-Community transactions between taxable persons in the EU covered by the EUROCANET system.
EUROCANET is used to identify risky taxable persons.
Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participant state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.
The NKU found both normal business incidents and those suspected of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected transactions.
The FÄ were only able to check high-risk transactions to a limited extent, especially in the case of so-called "Missing Traders," although an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxable person.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
it is advisable for customs and tax authorities to work more closely together to monitor the usefulness of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final consumer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to participate actively in EUROCANET because they do not believe that there is a sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that the German financial administration uses other instruments to identify risky taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft Regulation,
was created by EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should feed into the planned network to combat VAT fraud.
4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are dealt with in the same way.
The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKU compared the statistics that both Member States forwarded to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two Court of Auditors consider it useful to reopen the debate on statistics at EU level in order to avoid future inconsistencies.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should contain more information about the USt.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both Court of Auditors consider that Member States with a low recovery rate should endeavour to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should assist the Member States in this, if they so wish.
5. VAT test for large companies
The Court of Auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to the VAT audit of large companies in both states.
In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the financial administrations that they considered important in this context.
It became clear that the situation in both states is different.
For the selection of risky cases, the CZ has a system that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data, and profit and loss accounts).
The overall control of VAT can thus be effectively controlled and analysed.
A special financial office for large enterprises is to be set up in 2012.
Germany does not yet have a similar system, which makes it difficult to control and analyse the overall USt-control system.
The German financial administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the USt-Pre-Registrations or USt-Declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
