4. Audit of the management of turnover tax in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations of the first joint examination
4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for the registration of taxable persons within the EU
In response to the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended adapting the requirements for VAT registration and introducing new rules for the deletion of registration in the CZ.
These amended rules should reduce the risk of possible tax evasion more effectively.
In certain cases, it was found that the FÄ did not delete the VAT registration of taxable persons if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech Law No 235 / 2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT law").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to oblige the FÄ to be deleted if the taxable persons repeatedly do not submit VAT declarations.
According to the Czech VAT law, the FA may cancel the registration of a taxable person on its own initiative if (a) the taxable person has not made transactions for twelve consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for doing so; (b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the VAT law; (c) the taxable person no longer fulfils the conditions for the tax obligation.
The first investigation showed that, on the basis of the existing legal situation, FA Prague 1 must delete the VAT registration of "foreign taxable persons" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year if they were not obliged to register and pay USt in the current calendar year.
FA Prague 1 often did not delete the VAT registration of these taxable persons because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the VAT law, which entered into force on 1 January 2009.
Accordingly, the FA has the power to delete the registration of a foreign taxable person if he has not provided either taxable or tax-exempt supplies of goods or services entitled to deduction of VAT in the previous calendar year.
Recommendation 2
Monthly levy of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the Court of Auditors had recommended that the monthly levy of ZM be introduced.
The Council Directive, which shortened the turnaround for the levy of the ZM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the VAT Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be surrendered if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) of the VAT Act are provided to a person registered in another Member State as subject to turnover tax.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the tax for these services, which is the result of Council Directive 2008 / 8 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC as regards the place of the service.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data of the USt-Pre-Registrations and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data This recommendation related to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically compares the data on intra-Community transactions from the VAT declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of the UST is a prerequisite for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.
That is why the fight against VAT fraud is of paramount interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is demonstrated, among other things, by a study published by the European Commission in October 2009.
An external expert estimated the loss of VAT for the 25 Member States in the period 2000 to 2006. Based on the analysis of the available data, the tax loss for the aforementioned period was estimated at between EUR 90 and 113 billion, based on the fact that the EU-25 lose an average of 12% of their turnover taxes each year.
The estimated tax loss for CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that a Member State alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
With regard to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
Risky intra-Community transactions carried out by taxable persons within the EU and recorded in EUROCANET were selected for this purpose (see Chapter 4.3).
The aim of the EUROFISC network is to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively, and to improve cooperation between the competent authorities in order to detect fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to assess the risk potential of intra-Community transactions.
The ECOFIN Council 6 already approved EUROFISC on 7 October 2008 and at the same time adopted the principles governing the functioning of the system.
EUROCANET, developed by the Belgian financial administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, serves as a model for EUROFISC.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky transactions and to identify entrepreneurs involved in organised VAT fraud.
