4.2 Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
The first audit carried out a joint investigation into transactions where there were doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether there had been inconsistencies in the notifications of taxable persons in both Member States.
The two Court of Auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for which the tax examination by the FÄ of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint audit.
1)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxable person purchased goods worth €22,686 from a German taxable person.
The Czech taxable person did not declare the acquisition in his VAT declaration, since the German taxable period did not have a VAT identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German transactions.
By means of international administrative assistance pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that, according to German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need a VAT identification number in order to be able to benefit from the tax exemption for intra-Community supplies of goods.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that, according to the audit carried out by the competent Czech FA, the Czech taxable person submitted an additional VAT declaration declaring the purchase of goods of the abovementioned value and at the same time asserting his right to deduct VAT at the same level.
2)
A Czech taxable person is alleged to have purchased goods worth €12 561 from a German taxable person in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he said he had not purchased the goods and therefore did not declare them in his VAT statement.
The German financial administration, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, refused to deal with the request because the turnover associated with the acquisition did not exceed the threshold value of 15 000 euros.
As the Czech FA was unable to obtain documents, the tax audit remained inconclusive and the original tax fixing remained in place.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA received two spontaneous information from Germany in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, according to which the German taxable person had invoiced the delivery of the goods concerned to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxable person acquired the goods from the Slovak taxable person and stated the acquisition in his regular VAT declaration for the month of October 2004.
3)
A Czech taxable person is alleged to have purchased a car worth EUR 48 500 from a German taxable person in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he did not declare an intra-Community acquisition.
In addition, he had not issued a USt-Statement since August 2004, which is why the FA set the USt at CZK 0 for the quarter in question.
On the basis of information provided from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the FA requested the taxable person to submit a retrospective tax return in March 2007, but the taxable person failed to do so.
The audit found that the FA had carried out further investigations in this tax case in 2007, finding that the car in question had been sold by the taxable person to a used car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA carried out an assessment for the December 2004 tax period, setting additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings concerning the assets of the Czech taxable person; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax debt is likely to be unrecoverable.
4)
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxable person is said to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) worth a total of €198 167 to Germany.
In response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, it was stated that tax proceedings were pending against the German taxable person in Germany.
The audit carried out by the Federal Court of Auditors showed that, at the end of the proceedings, there was evidence of the involvement of the German taxable person in fraud.
The intra-Community purchase of goods was subject to labour taxation of €182 424 (for 2004) and €369 690 (for 2005).
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German tax administration, a VAT audit of the Czech taxable person has been carried out for the tax periods April, May and June 2005.
On the basis of the audit findings and the information from the international exchange of information, the FA set an additional tax of CZK 703 031 for May 2005 and CZK 726 551 for June 2005.
5)
The Czech taxable A is alleged to have purchased a machine with a total value of 58 000 euros from a German taxable person in February 2005.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxable person is said to have delivered a machine worth EUR 88 027 to the Czech taxable person B, but B denied the acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that B had acquired the machine from a German company with a branch in the CZ.
The Czech taxable A did not indicate the purchase of the goods from the aforementioned German taxable person in its VAT declaration.
The reply of the German FA to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 showed that the German taxable person had not made an intra-Community delivery of a machine worth 58 000 euros, but a delivery within the CZ.
In the audit, the Federal Court of Auditors found that the intra-Community supply of the machine was classified as a domestic supply after completion of an audit and that the VAT exemption was subsequently refused.
6)
A German taxable person is said to have delivered goods worth EUR 11 600 to a Czech taxable person in the third quarter of 2004.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany, i.e. in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA had made its assessment on the basis of a supplementary VAT declaration which unduly identified acquisitions from another Member State, including purchases in the above-mentioned amount.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that after receiving a reply to a request for information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the German FA corrected the VAT declaration of the German taxable person and set an additional tax of EUR 1 600.
An investigation is ongoing due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding VAT predisposition there.
The ZM of the German taxable person has not yet been corrected, as in Germany only the taxable person who has surrendered the ZM can correct it.
7)
The competent Czech FA received a request for information from the German tax administration in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the question of the purchase of a car worth EUR 47 400 by a Czech taxable person in February 2005.
After an audit for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA fixed the tax debt of the Czech taxable person at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the purchase of the car by the Czech taxable person.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the registration of the Czech taxable person had been deleted because he had not complied with his tax obligations.
The Czech FA had forwarded the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxable person has not yet corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax decision.
8)
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxable person supplied a Czech taxable person with a total value of €33,205, which he did not declare to be an intra-Community acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA investigated the reasons for the inconsistencies.
The Czech taxable person repeatedly issued subsequent VAT declarations for the first quarter of 2005.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference in the amount of acquisitions amounting to CZK 134 273 in the period from the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005 on the grounds that sales for individual quarters could not be accurately attributed and accepted the VAT declarations issued.
9)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxable person delivered goods worth EUR 46 854 to a Czech taxable person.
For the same period, the Czech taxable person declared the intra-Community purchase of goods worth only EUR 14 856.
In the context of the intergovernmental exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the Czech FA verified the actual value of the delivery.
The German reply to this question sent three invoices indicating a total value of the delivered goods of EUR 31 998, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech taxable person and the MIAS data.
According to the results of the audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors, following repeated warnings from the FA, the Czech taxable person submitted a retrospective VAT declaration for the July 2004 tax period in January 2007.
With this declaration, the taxable person simultaneously asserted his right to deduct VAT, and his tax liability for the tax period in question remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures relating to the transactions selected for the audit had been completed and that the financial administrations in the CZ and Germany had taken appropriate measures (including ex post VAT fixing or prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of risky intra-Community transactions
4.3.1 Findings in the Czech Republic
EUROCANET can be an important source of information to identify risky taxable persons in the Member State of acquisition.
In the CZ, the early-warning information obtained from EUROCANET is checked by the competent FA in the case of the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, CZ has included information on sales and taxable suppliers that are considered to be risky in the EUROCANET system.
Nine Czech taxable persons have been selected for the audit,
which had been entered into EUROCANET by the financial administrations of other Member States either as suppliers or purchasers.
