Since the German financial administration did not participate in the exchange of data via EUROCANET, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with a German VAT identification number were classified as risky by the German financial administration.
The investigation found both normal business incidents and those suspected of carousel fraud or other VAT fraud.
In these cases, the FÄ exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003,
For example:
• The FÄ did not find any suspicion of risky sales when examining the early warning information.
The taxable persons concerned were constantly monitored because their data was stored in EUROCANET.
• During the audits of risky transactions, the FÄ failed to demonstrate, on the basis of the accounting documents submitted, breaches of the rules on the calculation of the tax base and the tax, even though they found inconsistencies in the transport and storage of the goods or revealed business relations with letterbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual business incidents was complicated because certain taxable persons did not cooperate with the FÄ and could not be contacted.
The competent FÄ reviewed most of the risky taxable persons and transactions mentioned in early warning notifications from EUROCANET.
However, their ability to check risky transactions, especially so-called "Missing Traders," is limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly prove that the taxable person is acting fraudulently.
Stricter requirements for the registration of taxable persons for purposes of the UST and greater flexibility in the deletion of registrations would help to combat VAT fraud.
The taxable persons involved in fraudulent carousel transactions can be registered for the purposes of the USt in order to pretend fictitious deliveries of goods across the EU or to issue formally correct tax evidence to other taxable persons, with which they then assert unjustified claims for deduction of VAT.
In the case of suspected carousel fraud in connection with imports and exports, it is advisable that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to monitor the usefulness of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final consumer.
