The fact that three large Member States (Germany, Italy and the United Kingdom) did not participate was seen by the European Parliament at the end of 200811 as a weakness of the system, which was to be remedied by the establishment of a EUROFISC network with compulsory participation.
4.3.2 Findings in Germany
The Federal Court of Auditors evaluated data available to the Federal Central Tax Office, including data from EUROCANET.
They served as the basis for the selection of six German taxable persons whose files were checked.
Both Germany and a number of other countries refused to participate actively in EUROCANET.
That is why Germany has a passive status, which means that it does not send data to Brussels itself, but is only the recipient of EUROCANET data.
This is justified by the fact that "from the point of view of the Federal Government
no unambiguous legal basis [exists] that would allow the tax secrecy that exists in Germany to be broken.
In addition, the Federal Government does not have reliable information on how information sent by the Member States is processed within the framework of EUROCANET. "12 Since October 2007, the Federal Central Tax Office has been evaluating the EUROCANET data and transmitting it to the financial authorities of the Federal Government and the Länder on the basis of a coordinated procedure.
The German FÄ will receive control notifications on the direct business relations of the taxable persons registered with them with companies from other EU countries covered by EUROCANET.
However, the German FA does not receive any information as to whether the company from the aforementioned other EU Member State has business relations with a company established in another Member State, which is also in business with the German company under the control notice.
4.3.3 Evaluation
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has only a passive status.
From an active participant's point of view, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
Accordingly, the audit had to be carried out in different ways in this area.
However, there were no significant differences in the success of detecting VAT fraud, due to the fact that EUROCANET is only one component of the risk management system.
However, the financial administrations of both countries have a wide range of other tools at their disposal to detect fraudulent transactions, and yet it is necessary to develop a comprehensive risk management system within the EU.
The Council of the European Union agreed on a draft Regulation 13 establishing EUROFISC, a network for combating VAT fraud.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be shared by the Member States at European level and incorporated into this network.
