4.4 Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims in the EU is essentially based on:
Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, levies and customs duties;
Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC amending Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, levies and duties and as regards VAT and certain excise duties, and
Commission Directive 2002 / 94 / EC laying down detailed rules for the implementation of certain articles of Directive 76 / 308 / EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to certain levies, duties, taxes and other measures.
The CZ implemented Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC by Law No 252 / 2000 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
After the adoption of Council Directive 2001 / 44 / EC, it also had to be transposed into Czech law, and at the same time an amendment to the aforementioned law was necessary.
In this context, legislative amendment No 191 / 2004 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims was adopted.
A new key piece of legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179 / 2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this Regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009, and the Regulation also makes electronic transmission obligatory and obliges the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all documents sent with the original.
The main principles of international administrative assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. The principle of reciprocity applies;
2. Mutual assistance must always be provided only on request and subject to fulfilment of all conditions;
3. Mutual assistance does not extend to claims which are considered a criminal sanction in the requested State;
4. The intergovernmental assistance procedure for the recovery of claims must be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. In the recovery procedure, foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. Mutual assistance is provided only for the recovery of undisputed claims;
7. The principle of utilisation applies: the requesting State shall use all means to which it is entitled under national law to recover the claim.
Law No 191 / 2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: the provision of information, the notification of legal acts and the actual recovery.
Procedures for outgoing requests to other EU Member States
The competent FA shall electronically transmit the request for information, the request for notification of legal acts or the request for recovery, together with the relevant documents, to the Ministry of Finance of the CZ via the relevant Finance Directorate.
The Ministry of Finance of the CZ arranges the translation of the request into the language in question, scans it with all the installations and transmits it via the communication network or the CCN / CSI common interface to the competent financial authority of the State concerned.
A request for recovery aid must meet the following condition: the claim must exceed EUR 1 500 and must not be older than five years.
The requested authority may refuse recovery if the requirements are not met.
Procedure for incoming requests from other Member States
The Ministry of Finance of the CZ must confirm the receipt of requests from other Member States as soon as possible, at the latest within seven days.
If it decides not to accept the request, it must inform the requesting authority of the reasons for the rejection, specifying the specific provisions of the directive on which it is based.
The corresponding notification must be sent no later than three months after the date of receipt of the request.
Once the request has been received, the Ministry of Finance will check whether the request fulfils all legal requirements.
If the recovery request is granted, the FA shall, among other things, determine the debtor's assets, for example by extracts from the Land Registry, inquiries about existing bank accounts and registration of motor vehicles with the registration authority.
After six months from the date of receipt of the confirmation of receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance of the CZ shall inform the requesting authority of the outcome of the investigation carried out.
The requesting authority must also be informed if the taxable persons concerned are not reachable and the claim cannot therefore be recovered.
All sums successfully recovered must be transferred to the requesting authority within one month of recovery.
The Czech FA dealing with the recovery may, with the consent of the requesting state, agree on the claim or payment of instalments.
Interest or default surcharges imposed on the debtor for the period of delay pursuant to Law No 337 / 1992 on the management of taxes and fees
are the responsibility of the requesting State.
In particular in 2006 and 2007, the Ministry of Finance of the CZ delayed forwarding the recovery requests received to the competent FA.
The same applies to the forwarding of the recovery requests made by the Czech FÄ to the competent authority in the requested State.
The investigation revealed that the Ministry of Finance had breached the Law on Intergovernmental Assistance for the Recovery of Claims by failing to inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the state of play of the recovery procedure within six months of confirmation of receipt of the request.
The situation has improved since 2008.
Statistical data
In accordance with § 13 (4) of Law 191 / 2004, the Ministry of Finance of the CZ compiles a statistic for the European Commission by 15 March of the year, which contains the number of requests for information, notification of legal acts and recovery received in the previous year, including the amount of the respective claims.
On the basis of the data provided by the Member States, the European Commission draws up its report to the Council and the European Parliament on the application of the provisions on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims.
