4.4.4 Comparison and evaluation
In the case of recovery, all EU Member States are subject to the requirements of EU law for intergovernmental assistance.
The procedures for processing requests are therefore similar in the CZ and Germany.
The Federal Court of Auditors and the NKÚ have compared the statistics submitted by the two Member States to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
There were inconsistencies.
In its 200620 report, the European Commission recommended that Member States draw up their statistics with greater care.
In 200921, the Commission concluded that, despite a larger number of requests for assistance, the inconsistencies in the statistics have decreased.
Both auditors believe that a renewed debate at EU level on statistics would be useful in order to avoid the remaining inconsistencies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics are conditionally meaningful and cannot be used for comparisons.
In addition, the Court of Auditors considers that the statistics should show both the annual number of requests and the type of claims (e.g. VAT, income tax) and the amount of amounts collected per Member State.
By analysing more closely the statistics submitted by the Member States, the Commission could help Member States to assess their measures to combat VAT fraud.
Since the recovery rate can be calculated per Member State, the Court of Auditors argues that Member States with a low quota should at least aim for the average recovery rate within the EU.
At the request of a Member State, the Commission could play an active role in this.
The foreign recovery requests received by the CZ Ministry of Finance were forwarded to the relevant FÄ, particularly in 2006 and 2007, with a delay.
The same applies to the recovery requests made by the Czech FÄ.
The investigation showed that the Czech Ministry of Finance was in breach of Law No 191 / 2004 on Intergovernmental Recovery Assistance in so far as it did not inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the progress of recovery measures within the six-month period from the receipt of the request.
4.5 Value added tax audit for large companies
4.5.1 Value Added Tax Audit for large companies in the Czech Republic
General
The taxation procedure for large enterprises is subject to the same rules as for other taxable persons.
The audit of large enterprises is regulated by Czech Law No 337 / 1992, the "Tax and Fee Administration Act."
The Czech Ministry of Finance defines large enterprises as natural persons who have set up a business or legal persons who have been set up to carry out a business and whose net turnover for the tax period in question is at least CZK 2 billion, according to the income or corporate tax return.
The taxable person is classified as a large company on the basis of the turnover level according to the income or corporate tax return in the respective tax period; for the first time in 2003.
A natural or legal person will no longer be held as a large company for the purposes of sales taxation if, in three successive investment periods, their net turnover in the tax period is less than CZK 2 billion.
A taxable person can only be removed from the list of large companies if at least one type of tax has been examined beforehand for a tax period.
By the end of 2009, all large enterprises were audited at least every five years.
Since 2010, taxable persons have to be assessed in writing at least every two years, and the subsequent control measures are intended to eliminate the tax risks and their negative impact on the proper setting and collection of taxes.
The FÄ audits should focus on at least one type of tax; they usually cover several tax periods.
The large taxable enterprises were audited by the special audit bodies or audit services of the competent FÄ set up for a total of 13 FÄ.
A Special Audit Office carried out audits in its local area of responsibility in accordance with the instructions of the Head of the Finance Directorate.
She also checked
taxable persons with unusual and special business activities; and
those whose examination required a high degree of expertise and time.
Taxpayers with complex location distribution and organisational structure will also be examined,
Taxpayers suspected of large-scale tax evasion
as well as taxable persons belonging to chains and networks suspected of large-scale tax evasion and unjustified deduction.
